It was a pleasure working with Centene hiring managers in Tempe Area, to fill positions within 24 hours of work order! Effective and efficient employment services, AppleOne!
Still don't understand why people think bashing the competition is a good strategy. It says more about you or your product than anything else.

A prominent... personality... recently made a post about "questionable recruiting practices" and using candidates as "human fishing lures".  I use this "questionable practice" all the time. Example...
Someone I placed 3+ years ago was laid off last week. I didn't have an opening for him, but I wanted to help him.
I called companies hiring for his skill set, telling them I "knew a guy". Leveraging his experience, I was able to get a contract signed with a company I've never done business with before.
He completed his phone interview on Monday and he's interviewing onsite tomorrow. He's thrilled. This is an every day thing for me.
What's so "questionable" about this practice? When did helping people FOR FREE become so "questionable"? When did recruiters bashing other recruiters become so "trendy"?
